{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 1}Now, after the death of Saul, when David had returned from smitting the Amalekites, David remained two days in Ziklag.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}Then on the third day there came a man out of the camp from Saul, with his clothes torn and with earth upon his head. And as soon as he came to David, he fell to the earth and did obeisance.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}And David said to him, \uc1\u8220*Whence do you come?\uc1\u8221* And he answered him, \uc1\u8220*From the camp of Israel have I escaped.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}And David said to him, \uc1\u8220*How was the affair? Tell me.\uc1\u8221* And he answered, \uc1\u8220*The people fled from the battle, and many of the people , and also Saul and Jonathan his son are dead.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}Then David said to the young man who told him, \uc1\u8220*How do you know that Saul and Jonathan his son are dead?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}And the young man who told him said, \uc1\u8220*I happened to be on Mount Gilboa, just as Saul was leaning on his spear, and as the chariots and horsemen were following close after him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}And when he looked behind him, he saw me and called to me. And I answered, \uc1\u8216*Here am I.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}And he said to me, \uc1\u8216*Who are you?\uc1\u8217* And I replied, \uc1\u8216*I am an Amalekite.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}And he said to me, \uc1\u8216*Stand, I pray, before me and slay me, for dizziness has seized me, because my life is yet whole in me.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}So I stood before him and slew him, because I was sure that he could not live after he had fallen; and I took the crown that was upon his head, and the armlet that was on his arm, and have brought them here to my lord.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Then David took hold of his clothes and tore them; and all the men who were with him did likewise.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}And they mourned and wept and fasted until evening for Saul and for Jonathan his son and for the people of Jehovah and for the house of Israel, because they had fallen by the sword.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}And David said to the young man who told him, \uc1\u8220*Whence do you come?\uc1\u8221* And he answered, \uc1\u8220*I am the son of an Amalekite sojourner.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}And David said to him, \uc1\u8220*How is it that you were not afraid to put forth your hand to destroy Jehovah\uc1\u8217*s anointed?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}Then David called one of the young men, and said, \uc1\u8220*Go near and strike him down.\uc1\u8221* Accordingly he smote him, so that he died.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}And David said to him, \uc1\u8220*Your blood be upon your head, for your own mouth testified against you, when you said, \uc1\u8216*I have slain Jehovah\uc1\u8217*s anointed.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}Then David sang this dirge over Saul and Jonathan his son{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}(behold, it is written in the Book of Jashar), and said,
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
Weep, O Judah!
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}Grieve, O Israel!
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
On thy heights are the slain!
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
How have the mighty fallen!
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}Tell it not in Gath,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
Declare it not in the streets of Askelon;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
Lest the daughters of the Philistines rejoice,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
Lest the daughters of the uncircumcised exult.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}Ye mountains of Giboa, may no dew descend,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Nor rain upon you, O ye fields of !
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
For there was the shield of the mighty cast away,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
The shield of Saul, not anointed with oil.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}From the blood of the slain,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
From the fat of the mighty,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
The bow of Jonathan turned not back,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
The sword of Saul returned not empty.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}Saul and Jonathan, the beloved and the lovely!
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
In life and in death they were not parted;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
They were swifter than eagles.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
They were stronger than lions.
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Daughters of Israel, weep over Saul,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
Who clothed you daintily in fine linen,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
Who put golden ornaments on your garments, :
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}\uc1\u8220*How have the mighty fallen in the midst of battle!\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}I am distressed for thee, my brother Jonathan!
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
Thou wert surpassingly dear to me,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
Thy love to me was far more than the love of woman!
\par}

{\pard 

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}How have the mighty fallen,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
And the weapons of war perished!
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 2}Now after this David inquired of Jehovah, saying, \uc1\u8220*Shall I go up to one of the cities of Judah?\uc1\u8221* And Jehovah answered him, \uc1\u8220*Go up.\uc1\u8221* And when David said, \uc1\u8220*Whither shall I go up,\uc1\u8221* he said, \uc1\u8220*To Hebron.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}So David went up with his two wives, Ahinoam, the Jezreelitess, and Abigail, the wife of Nabal the Carmelite.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}And David brought up the men who were with him, each with his household, and they dwelt in the towns of Hebron.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}And the men of Judah came and there anointed David king over the house of Judah.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
And when they told David about the men of Jabesh in Gilead who had buried Saul,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}David sent messengers to the men of Jabesh in Gilead and said to them, \uc1\u8220*May you be blest of Jehovah, because you have shown this kindness to your lord Saul and have buried him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}Even so may Jehovah show kindness and truth to you; and I also will do well by you, because you have done this thing.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}Now therefore be courageous and valiant; for Saul your lord is dead, and the house of Judah have anointed me king over them.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Now Abner the son of Ner, commander of Saul\uc1\u8217*s army, had taken  the son of Saul, and brought him over to Mahanaim.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}And he made him king over Gilead and the Ashurites and Jezreel and Ephraim and Benjamin and all Israel.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}(Ishbaal, Saul\uc1\u8217*s son, was forty years old when he became king over Israel, and he reigned two years). But the house of Judah followed David.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}And the time that David was king in Hebron over the house of Judah, was seven years and six months.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Now Abner the son of Ner and the servants of Ishbaal the son of Saul went out from Mahanaim to Gibeon.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}And Joab the son of Zeruiah and the servants of David went out and met them at the pool of Gibeon. And they sat down, the one on the one side of the pool and the other on the other side of the pool.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}Then Abner said to Joab, \uc1\u8220*Let the young men arise and play before us.\uc1\u8221* And Joab said, \uc1\u8220*Let them arise.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}Then they arose and went over by number: twelve for Benjamin and Ishbaal the son of Saul, and twelve of the servants of David.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}And they each caught his opponent by the head and thrust his sword into his side, so they fell down together. Therefore that place was called, Field of the Enemies (which is in Gibeon).{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}And the battle was very fierce that day, and Abner and the men of Israel were vanquished before the servants of David.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}And the three sons of Zeruiah were there, Joab, Abishai, and Asahel; and Asahel was as swift of foot as one of the gazelles which are in the field.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}And Asahel pursued Abner; and as he went he turned neither to the right nor to the left from the pursuit of Abner.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}Then Abner looked behind him and said, \uc1\u8220*Is it you, Asahel?\uc1\u8221* And he answered, \uc1\u8220*It is I.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}Therefore Abner said to him, \uc1\u8220*Turn aside to your right or to your left and seize one of the young men and take his spoil.\uc1\u8221* But Asahel would not turn aside from pursuing him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}Therefore Abner said again to Asahel, \uc1\u8220*Turn aside from following me. Why should I smite you to the ground? How then could I look Joab your brother in the face?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}But he refused to turn aside. Therefore Abner smote him with a backward stroke in the body, so that the spear came out at his back; and he fell there and died in his place. Then all who came to the place where Asahel had fallen and died, stood still. 
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}But Joab and Abishai pursued after Abner. And as the sun was setting, they came to the hill of Ammah, which is before Giah on the highway in the Wilderness of Gibeon.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}And the Benjamites assembled behind Abner and formed a solid phalanx, and stood on the top of a hill.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}Then Abner called to Joab and said, \uc1\u8220*Shall the sword devour forever? Do you not know that the end will be bitterness? How long then will it be before you command the people to turn from pursuing their kinsmen?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}And Joab said, \uc1\u8220*As  liveth, if you had not spoken, then assuredly not until morning would the people have ceased each from pursuing his brother.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}So Joab blew the trumpet; and all the people stool still and pursued Israel no more, nor did they fight any more.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}But Abner and his men marched all that night through the Arabah and crossed the Jordan and went through the whole Bithron and came to Mahanaim.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}And Joab returned from the pursuit of Abner. And when he had gathered all the people together, nineteen of David\uc1\u8217*s servants beside Asahel were missing;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}while the servants of David had smitten of Benjamin and of Abner\uc1\u8217*s men three hundred and sixty .{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}And they took up Asahel and buried him in his father\uc1\u8217*s sepulchre, which was in Bethlehem. And Joab and his men marched all night, and day dawned upon them at Hebron.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 3}And the war between the house of Saul and the house of David was prolonged; but David kept growing stronger, while the house of Saul grew gradually weaker.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}Now in Hebron sons were born to David: his eldest was Amnon the son of Ahinoam the Jezreelitess;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}and his second, Chileab the son of Abigail, the wife of Nabal the Carmelite; and the third, Absalom the son of Maacah, the daughter of Talmai king of Geshur;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}and the fourth, Adonijah the son of Haggith; and the fifth, Shephatiah the son of Abital;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}and the sixth, Ithream the son of Eglah, David\uc1\u8217*s wife. These were born to David in Hebron.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}Now, while there was war between the house of Saul and the house of David, Abner made himself strong in the house of Saul.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}And Saul had a concubine, whose name was Rizpah, the daughter of Aiah. And  said to Abner, \uc1\u8220*Why do you go in unto my father\uc1\u8217*s concubine?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Then Abner was very angry because of the words of Ishbaal and said, \uc1\u8220*Am I a , who am at this time showing kindness to the house of Saul your father, to his kinsmen, and to his friends, and have not delivered you into the hand of David, that you now charge me with guilt in connection with a woman?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}God do to Abner whatever he pleases, if, as Jehovah hath sworn to David, I do not even so to him,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}by transferring the kingdom from the house of Saul and by establishing the throne of David over Israel and over Judah from Dan to Beersheba.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}And he did not dare to make Abner any answer, for he feared him.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}So Abner sent messengers to David to  saying, \uc1\u8220*Make your league with me, then I will co-operate with you in bringing over all Israel to you.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}And he said, \uc1\u8220*Good, I will make a league with you, but one thing I require of you, that is, you shall not see my face unless you bring Michal, Saul\uc1\u8217*s daughter, when you come to see me.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}Then David sent messengers to Ishbaal, Saul\uc1\u8217*s son, saying, Give me my wife Michal, whom I bought for a hundred foreskins of the Philistines.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}And Ishbaal sent and took her from her husband, Paltiel the son of Laish.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}But her husband followed her, weeping as he went, to Bahurim. Then Abner said to him, \uc1\u8220*Go, return\uc1\u8221*; and he returned.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}Now Abner had entered into communication with the elders of Israel, saying, \uc1\u8220*Already for a long time you have been desirous of having David king over you.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}Now do it, for Jehovah hath spoken of David, saying, \uc1\u8216*By the hand of my servant David will I save my people Israel out of the hand of the Philistines and out of the hand of all their enemies?\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}Abner also spoke in the ears of Benjamin and went to communicate directly to David in Hebron all that seemed good to Israel and to the whole house of Benjamin.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}And when Abner came to David at Hebron, accompanied by twenty men, David gave Abner and the men who were with him a feast.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}And Abner said to David, \uc1\u8220*I will arise and go and will gather all Israel to my lord the king, that they may make a covenant with you and that you may be king over all which you desire.\uc1\u8221* Then David sent Abner away, and he went in peace.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}Just then the servants of David and Joab came from a raid, and brought in with them great spoil; but Abner was not with David in Hebron, for he had sent him away and he had gone in peace.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}So when Joab and all the band that was with him came home, they told Joab, saying, \uc1\u8220*Abner the son of Ner came to the king, and he has sent him away, and he has gone in peace.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Then Joab went to the king and said, \uc1\u8220*What have you done? Behold, Abner came to you; why have you now sent him away, so that he is gone?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}Do you not know that Abner the son of Ner came to deceive you and to note your going out and your coming in and to know all that you are doing?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}And when Joab came out from David, he sent messengers after Abner and they brought him back from the Cistern of Sirah without David\uc1\u8217*s knowing it.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}And when Abner returned to Hebron, Joab took him apart to the  of the gate to speak with him quietly and smote him there in the body. So he died for the blood of Asahel Joab\uc1\u8217*s brother.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}But afterward when David heard it, he said, \uc1\u8220*I and my kingdom are forever guiltless before Jehovah of the blood of Abner the son of Ner.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}May it fall upon the head of Joab and upon all his father\uc1\u8217*s house, and may there not fail from the house of Joab one who has an issue, or who is a leper, or who is effeminate, or who falls by the sword, or who lacks bread.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}But Joab and Abishai his brother slew Abner, because he had killed their brother Asahel at Gibeon in the battle.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}And David said to Joab, and to all the people who were with him, \uc1\u8220*Tear your clothes, and gird yourselves with sackloth, and mourn before Abner!\uc1\u8221* And King David followed the bier.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}And when they buried Abner in Hebron, the king wept with a loud voice at the grave of Abner, and all the people wept.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}And the king sang a dirge for Abner and said,
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
Must Abner die as dies the impious fool?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}Thy hands were not bound,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
Thy feet were not put into fetters;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
As one falls before ruthless men, thou didst fall.
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24 
Then all the people wept still more over him.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 35}Afterwards all the people came to urge David to eat bread while it was yet day; but David took oath, saying, \uc1\u8220*God do to me whatever he will, if I taste bread or anything else before the sun goes down.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 36}And when all the people observed it, they were pleased;  everything that the king did pleased all the people.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 37}So all the people and all Israel understood that day that the king had nothing to do with the slaying of Abner the son of Ner.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 38}And the king said to his servants, \uc1\u8220*Do you not know that a prince and a great man has fallen to-day in Israel?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 39}And I am this day weak, though anointed king, for these men, the sons of Zeruiah, are too strong for me. May Jehovah requite the evildoer according to his wickedness!\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 4}Now when Ishbaal, Saul\uc1\u8217*s son, heard that Abner was dead in Hebron, his hands became limp and all the Israelites were thrown into confusion.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}And Ishbaal, Saul\uc1\u8217*s son, had two men who were captains of guerilla bands: the name of the one was Baanah, and the name of the other Rechab, sons of Rimmon the Beerothite, of the Benjamites (for Beeroth is also reckoned to Benjamin,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}and the Beerothites fled to Gittaim and have been sojourners there until this day).
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Now Jonathan, Saul\uc1\u8217*s son, had a son who was lame in his feet. He was five years old when the news came from Jezreel regarding Saul and Jonathan. And his nurse took him up and fled, and while she was hastily fleeing, he fell and became lame. And his name was Meribaal.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}And the sons of Rimmon the Beerothite, Rechab and Baanah, went and came about mid-day to the house of Ishbaal, as he was taking his rest at noon.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}And just then the doorkeeper of the palace was cleaning wheat, and she became drowsy and slept. So Rechab and Baanah his brother slipt in and thus entered the house, while the king was lying on his bed in his sleeping room, and they smote and killed him and cut off his head.  
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}Then they took his head and went all night by the way of the Arabah.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}And they brought the head of Ishbaal to David to Hebron and said to the king, \uc1\u8220*Here is the head of Ishbaal, the son of Saul your enemy, who sought your life. But Jehovah hath avenged my lord the king this day on Saul and his descendants.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}Then David answered Rechab and Baanah his brother, the sons of Rimmon the Beerothite, and said to them, \uc1\u8220*As Jehovah liveth, who hath delivered my life out of all adversity,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}when one told me, saying, \uc1\u8216*Behold, Saul is dead,\uc1\u8217* thinking to have brought good news, I took hold of him, and slew him in Ziklag, .{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}How much more, when wicked men have slain a righteous person in his own house upon his own bed, shall I not now require his blood from you and destroy you from the earth?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Then David commanded his young men, and they slew them and cut off their hands and their feet, and hanged them up beside the pool in Hebron. But the head of Ishbaal they took and buried in the grave of Abner at Hebron.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 5}Then all the tribes of Israel came to David to Hebron and said, \uc1\u8220*See, we are your bone and your flesh.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}In times past when Saul was king over us, it was you who led out and brought in Israel, and Jehovah has said to you, \uc1\u8216*Thou shalt be shepherd of my people Israel, and thou shalt be prince over Israel.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}And all the elders of Israel came to the king to Hebron, and King David made a covenant with them in Hebron before Jehovah, and they anointed David king over Israel.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}David was thirty years old when he became king, and reigned forty years.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}In Hebron he reigned over Judah seven years and six months, and in Jerusalem he reigned thirty-three years over all Israel and Judah.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}Then the king and his men went to Jerusalem against the Jebusites, the inhabitants of the land, who spoke to David, saying, \uc1\u8220*You shall not come in here, but the blind and the lame shall turn you away\uc1\u8221*, thinking, \uc1\u8220*David cannot come in here.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}Nevertheless David took the stronghold of Zion (that is the city of David).{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}And David said on that day, \uc1\u8220*Whoever smites the Jebusites, let him get up through the watercourse and smite the lame and the blind, whom David\uc1\u8217*s soul hates.\uc1\u8221* Therefore it is said, \uc1\u8220*The blind and the lame cannot come into the temple.\uc1\u8221* {\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}Then David dwelt in the stronghold, and called it the City of David. And David constructed an encircling wall from Millo and inwards.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}And David kept on growing greater, for  of hosts was with him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}And Hiram king of Tyre sent messengers to David, and cedar trees and carpenters and masons and they built David a palace.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Thus David perceived that Jehovah had established him king over Israel,  for the sake of his people Israel.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}And in Jerusalem David took for himself more concubines and wives, after he came there from Hebron; and more sons and daughters were born to David.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}And these are the names of those who were born to him in Jerusalem: Shammaua, Shobab, Nathan, Solomon,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}Ibhar, Elishua, Nepheg, Japhia,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}Elishama, , and Eliphelet.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}Now when the Philistines heard that they had anointed David king over Israel, all the Philistines went up to seek David; and when David heard of this he went down to the stronghold.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}Now the Philistines had come and spread themselves out in the valley of Rephaim.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}And David inquired of Jehovah, saying, \uc1\u8220*Shall I go up against the Philistines? Wilt thou deliver them into my hand?\uc1\u8221* And Jehovah said to David, \uc1\u8220*Go up; for I will certainly deliver the Philistines into thy hand.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}And David came to Baal-perazim, and David smote them there; and he said, \uc1\u8220*Jehovah hath broken down mine enemies before me, like the breaking of waters.\uc1\u8221* Therefore he called the name of that place Baal-perazim (Lord of the breakings through).{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}And they left their  there, and David and his men carried them away.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}And the Philistines came up yet again and spread themselves out in the valley of Rephaim.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}And when David inquired of Jehovah, he said, \uc1\u8220*Thou shalt not go up; go about to their rear and come upon them opposite the balsam trees.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}And when thou hearest the sound of marching in the tops of the balsam trees, make haste, for then Jehovah has gone out before thee to smite the camp of the Philistines.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}And David did as Jehovah commanded him, and smote the Philistines from  as far as Gezer.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 6}Then David again assembled all the chosen men of Israel, thirty thousand.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}And David arose and went with all the people who were with him, to Baal-Judah, to bring up from there the ark of God which is called by the name of Jehovah of hosts who sits enthroned upon the cherubim.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}And they set the ark of God upon a new cart, and brought it out of the house of Abinadab, that was on the hill, with Uzzah and Ahio the sons of Abinadab guiding the cart: Uzzah went with the ark of God,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4} while Ahio went before the ark.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}And David and all the house of Israel were dancing before Jehovah with all their might and with songs and harps and lyres and cymbals.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}And when they came to the threshing-floor of Nacon, Uzzah stretched out his hand to the ark of God to hold it, for the oxen slipped.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}Then the anger of Jehovah was aroused against Uzzah and God smote him there because , so that he died there in the presence of God.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}And David was angry because he had broken forth upon Uzzah. Therefore that place is called Perez-uzzah (Breach of Uzzah) to this day.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}And David was afraid of Jehovah that day so that he said, \uc1\u8220*How can the ark of Jehovah come to me?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}And David was unwilling to remove the ark of Jehovah to the city of David, but carried it aside into the house of Obed-edom the Gitite.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}So the ark remained in the house of Obed-edom the Gittite three months. And Jehovah blessed Obed-edom and all his house.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}And when the report came to King David: \uc1\u8220*Jehovah hath blessed Obed-edom and all his house because of the ark of God\uc1\u8221*, David went and brought up with joy the ark of God from the house of Obed-edom to the city of David.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}And when the bearers of the ark of Jehovah had gone six paces, he sacrificed an ox and a fatling.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}And David was dancing before Jehovah with all his might, and David was girded with a linen ephod.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}So David and all the house of Israel brought up the ark of Jehovah with shouting, and the sound of the trumpet.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}Now when the ark of Jehovah was coming into the city of David, Michal the daughter of Saul looked out of the window, and when she saw King David leaping and dancing before Jehovah, she despised him in her heart.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}And when they brought in the ark of Jehovah and set it in its place in the midst of the tent that David had pitched for it, David offered burnt-offerings and peace-offerings before Jehovah.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}And when David had finished sacrificing the burnt-offering and the peace-offerings, he blessed the people in the name of Jehovah of hosts.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}And he distributed to all the people even among the whole multitude of Israel, both men and women, to each a cake of bread, a portion of meat, and a bunch of raisins. Then all the people departed each to his home.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}But when David returned to greet his family, Michal the daughter of Saul came out to meet David and said, \uc1\u8220*How glorious was the king of Israel as he exposed himself to the eyes of his servants\uc1\u8217* maids, as one of the vain fellows shamelessly exposes himself!\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}And David said to Michal, \uc1\u8220*It was before Jehovah  who chose me rather than your father and rather than any of his family to appoint me as prince over the people of Jehovah, over Israel. Therefore I will sport before Jehovah{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}and I will be yet more lightly esteemed than this and I will be despised . But of the maids of whom you have spoken I shall indeed be held in honor.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}And Michal the daughter of Saul had no child to the day of her death.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 7}Now when David had taken possession of his palace, Jehovah having given him rest around about from all his enemies,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}the king said to Nathan the prophet, \uc1\u8220*See now, I dwell in a house of cedar, but the ark of God dwells within tent-curtains.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}And Nathan said to the king, \uc1\u8220*Go, do all that you purpose for Jehovah is with you.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}But during the same night the word of Jehovah came to Nathan, saying,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}\uc1\u8220*Go and tell my servant David, \uc1\u8216*Thus saith Jehovah, \uc1\u8220*Shouldst thou build a temple for me to dwell in?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}I have not dwelt in a temple since the day that I brought up the Israelites from Egypt, even to this day, but have gone about in a tent-dwelling.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}As long as I went about with all the Israelites, did I say anything to one of Israel\uc1\u8217*s , whom I commanded to be a shepherd to my people Israel, saying: \uc1\u8216*Why have ye not built me a house of cedar?\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Now therefore thus shalt thou say to my servant David, \uc1\u8216*Thus saith Jehovah of hosts, \uc1\u8220*I took thee from the pasture, from after the sheep, that thou shouldest be prince over my people, over Israel;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}and I have been with thee wherever thou didst go, to destroy all thine enemies from before thee, and I will make thee a , like the name of the great in the earth.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}And I will appoint a place for my people Israel, and I will plant them, that they may dwell in their own place, and be moved no more, and the wicked shall no more afflict them as formerly,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}from the day that I appointed judges over my people Israel.
