{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}Then King David went in and sat before Jehovah and said, \uc1\u8220*Who am I, O Lord Jehovah, and what is my house, that thou hast brought me thus far?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}And this was too small a thing in thine eyes, O Lord Jehovah, that thou hast spoken also concerning thy servant\uc1\u8217*s house for distant times, and {\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}And what shall David say more to thee, for thou knowest thy servant, O Lord Jehovah?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}For thy servant\uc1\u8217*s sake and according to thine heart hast thou done .{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}Therefore thou art great, O Jehovah  God, for there is none like thee, neither is there any God besides thee, according to all that we have heard with our ears.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}And what other nation in the earth is like thy people Israel, whom a God went to redeem for himself as a people, to make him a name and to do for  great and terrible things {\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}But thou didst establish thy people Israel as thine own people forever, and thou, Jehovah, hast become their God.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}And now, O Lord Jehovah, confirm forever the promise that thou hast made concerning thy servant and concerning his house, and do as thou hast promised,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}that thy name be great forever, in that it will be said, \uc1\u8216*Jehovah of hosts is God over Israel; and the house of thy servant David shall be established before thee.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}For thou, O Jehovah of hosts, the God of Israel, hast revealed to thy servant, saying, \uc1\u8216*I will build thee a house;\uc1\u8217* therefore hath thy servant found courage to pray this prayer to thee.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}And now, O Lord Jehovah, thou art God, and thy words are truth, and thou hast promised this good thing to thy servant;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}now therefore may it please thee to bless the house of thy servant that it may continue forever before thee! For thou, O Lord Jehovah, hast spoken it, and with thy blessing will the house of thy servant be forever blessed.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 8}And after this David smote the Philistines, and subdued them; and David took the bridle of the mother city out of the hand of the Philistines.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}Then  smote Moab and measured them off with a line, making them lie down on the ground; and he measured  to put to death and one full line to save alive. And thus the Moabites became subject to David, and brought a present.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}Thus David smote Hadadezer the son of Rehob, the king of Zobah, as he went to establish his rule at the River Euphrates.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}And David took from him , and twenty thousand footmen: and David hamstrung all the chariot horses leaving only a hundred of them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}And when the Arameans of Damascus came to help Hadadezer king of Zobah, David smote of the Arameans twenty thousand men.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}Then David put garrisons in Aram of Damascus, and the Arameans became subject to David and brought a present. And Jehovah helped David wherever he went.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}And David took the shields of gold that were on on the servants of Hadadezer, and brought them to Jerusalem.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}And from  and from Berothai, cities of Hadadezer, King David took a great amount of brass.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}And when  king of Hamath heard that David had smitten all the army of Hadadezer,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10} sent  his son to King David, to greet him and to wish him good fortune, because he had fought against Hadadezer and smitten him, for Hadadezer was  military antagonist. And he brought with him vessels of silver, of gold, and of brass.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}These also King David dedicated to Jehovah, with the silver and gold that he dedicated from all the nations that he subdued--{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}from , Moab, the Ammonites, the Philistines, and Amalek, and from the spoil of Hadadezer son of Rehob, king of Zobah.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}Then David made a reputation for himself. On his return, he smote of the Edomites in the Valley of Salt, eighteen thousand men.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}And he put garrisons in all Edom; and all the Edomites became subject to David. And Jehovah helped David wherever he went.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}And David was king over all Israel. And David administered justice and righteousness to all his people.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}And Joab the son of Zeruiah was in command of the army, and Jehoshaphat the son of Ahilud was chancellor,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}and Zadok  and  the son of  were priests, and  was scribe,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}and Benaiah the son of Jehoida was in command of the Cherethites and the Pelethites, and David\uc1\u8217*s sons were priests.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 9}And David said, \uc1\u8220*Is there left of the house of Saul any to whom I may show kindness for Jonathan\uc1\u8217*s sake?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}Now there was of the house of Saul a servant whose name was Ziba, and they called him to David. And the king Said to him, \uc1\u8220*Are you Ziba?\uc1\u8221* And he said, \uc1\u8220*Your servant am I.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}The king said, \uc1\u8220*Is there no one else belonging to the house of Saul to whom I may show the kindness of God?\uc1\u8221* And Ziba said to the king, \uc1\u8220*Jonathan has still a son, who is lame in his feet.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}And the king said to him, \uc1\u8220*Where is he?\uc1\u8221* And Ziba said to the king, \uc1\u8220*Behold he is in the house of Machir the son of Ammiel, in Lodebar.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}Then King David sent and brought him from the house of Machir the son of Ammiel, from Lodebar.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}And when Meribaal the son of Jonathan, the son of Saul, came to David, he fell on his face and did obeisance. David said, \uc1\u8220*Meribaal!\uc1\u8221* And he answered, \uc1\u8220*Behold your servant!\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}Then David said to him, \uc1\u8220*Fear not for I will surely show you kindness for the sake of Jonathan your father and will restore to you all the land of Saul your ancestor; and you shall eat my table continually.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}And he did obeisance and said, \uc1\u8220*What is your servant that you should look favorably upon such a dead dog as I am?\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}Then the king called to Ziba, Saul\uc1\u8217*s servant, and said to him, \uc1\u8220*All that belongs to Saul and all his house have I given to your master\uc1\u8217*s son.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}And you shall cultivate the land for him, together with your sons and servants, and bring in the fruits that you master\uc1\u8217*s son may have food to eat; but Meribaal your master\uc1\u8217*s son shall always eat bread at my table.\uc1\u8221* Now Ziba had fifteen sons and twenty servants.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Then said Ziba to the king, \uc1\u8220*Just as my lord the king commands his servant, so will your servant do.\uc1\u8221* So Meribaal ate at  table like one of the sons of the king.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}And Meribaal had a young son, whose name was Mica. And all who dwelt in the house of Ziba were Meribaal\uc1\u8217*s servants.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}So Meribaal dwelt in Jerusalem, for he ate continually at the king\uc1\u8217*s table, being lame in both feet.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 10}Now it came to pass after this, that the king of the Ammonites died and Hanun his son became king in his place.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}And David said, \uc1\u8220*I will show kindness to Hanun the son of Nahash as his father showed kindness to me.\uc1\u8221* So David sent by his servants to console with him concerning his father. But when David\uc1\u8217*s servants came to the land of the Ammonites,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}the princes of the Ammonites said to Hanun their lord, \uc1\u8220*Do you suppose that David is honoring your father in sending comforters to you? Has not David sent his servants to you to search the city and to spy it out and to overthrow it?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}So Hanun took David\uc1\u8217*s servants, and shaved off the one half of their beards, cut their robes in two, even to their hips, and sent them away.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}When David was informed , he sent to meet them, for the men were greatly ashamed. And the king said, \uc1\u8220*Stay at Jericho until your beards are grown and then return.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}Now when the Ammonites saw that they had become odious to David, the Ammonites sent and hired the Arameans of Beth-rehob, and the Arameans of Zobah, twenty thousand footmen, and the king of Maacah and of Ishtob with twelve thousand men.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}And when David heard of it, he sent Joab and all  and the trained warriors.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}And the Ammonites came out, and drew up in battle-array at the entrance of the city. And the Arameans of Zobah and Rehob, and Ishtob and Maacah, were by themselves in the open country.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}But when Joab saw that he was being attacked both in front and in the rear, he selected the picked men of Israel, and put them in array against the Arameans.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}And the rest of the people he placed under the command of Abishai his brother; and he put them in array against the Ammonites.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}And he said, \uc1\u8220*If the Arameans should be too strong for me, then you shall help me, but if the Ammonites should be too strong for you, then I will come to your aid.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Be courageous and let us know ourselves men for the sake of our people and for the cities of our God; and may Jehovah do that which seems good to him.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}Now when Joab and the people who were with him drew near for the battle against the Arameans, they fled before him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}And when the Ammonites saw that the Arameans had fled, they likewise fled before Abishai, and entered into the city. Then Joab returned from the Ammonites, and came to Jerusalem.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}But when the Arameans saw that they had been defeated by the Israelites, they gathered themselves together,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}and  sent, and brought out the Arameans who were beyond the River (Euphrates), and they came to Helam with Shobach, the commander of the army of Hadadezer, at their head.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}And when it was reported to David, he gathered all Israel together and crossed over the Jordan and came to Helam. And the Arameans set themselves in array against David and fought with him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}And the Arameans fled before Israel; and David slew of the Arameans seven hundred  and forty thousand  and smote Shobach the commander of their army, so that he died there.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}And when all the kings who were subject to Hadadezer saw that they were defeated by Israel, they made peace with Israel and were subject to them. So the Arameans feared to help the Ammonites any more.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 11}Now, a year later, at the time when  are accustomed to go forth, David sent Joab and his servants with him, even all Israel; and they destroyed the Ammonites, and besieged Rabbah. But David remained at Jerusalem.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}Now once at eventide, while Joab was besieging Rabbath-Ammon, David arose from his bed, and walked upon the roof of the king\uc1\u8217*s palace; and from the roof he saw a woman bathing. And the woman was very beautiful.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}And David sent to inquire concerning the woman. And one said, \uc1\u8220*Is not this Bathsheba, the wife of Uriah the Hittite?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Then David sent messengers to take her; and she came to him, and he lay with her--she having been purified from her uncleanness. Then she returned to her house.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}And the woman conceived; and she sent to tell David, saying, \uc1\u8220*I am with child.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}Then David said to Joab, Send me Uriah the Hittite. And Joab sent Uriah to David.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}And when Uriah had come to him, David asked him concerning the welfare of Joab and the people and the progress of the war.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Then David said to Uriah, \uc1\u8220*Go down to your house and wash your feet.\uc1\u8221* And Uriah departed from the king\uc1\u8217*s house, and there followed him a portion from the king.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}But Uriah slept at the door of the king\uc1\u8217*s house with the servants of his lord and did not go down to his house.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}Now when it was told David, Uriah did not go down to his house, \uc1\u8220*David said to Uriah, have you not come from a journey? Why did you not go down to your house?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}But Uriah said to David, \uc1\u8220*The ark and Israel and Judah are abiding in huts, and my master Joab, and the servants of my lord are camping in the open fields; shall I then go to my house to eat and drink and to lie with my wife! , I cannot do this.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Then David said to Uriah, \uc1\u8220*Stay here to-day also, and to-morrow I will let you go.\uc1\u8221* So Uriah remained in Jerusalem {\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}David invited him and he ate and drank before him, so that he made drunk. Then in the evening he went out to lie on his couch with the servants of his lord, but went not down to his house.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}And in the morning, David wrote a letter to Joab, and sent it by Uriah.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}And he wrote in the letter saying, \uc1\u8220*Set Uriah in the face of the fiercest fighting, then retreat from behind him, that he may be smitten and die.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}So in keeping guard over the city, Joab assigned Uriah to the place where he knew valiant men were.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}And when the city went out to fight with Joab, there fell some of the soldiers of David, and Uriah the Hittite fell also.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}Then Joab sent to tell David all the facts concerning the war.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}And he instructed the messenger, saying, \uc1\u8220*When you have finished telling all the facts concerning the war to the king,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}then if the king\uc1\u8217*s wrath is aroused, and he say to you, \uc1\u8216*Why did you go so near to the city to fight? Did you not know that they would shoot from the wall?{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}Who smote Abimelech the son of Jerubbaal? Did not a woman cast an upper millstone upon him from the wall, so that he died at Thebez? Why did you go near the wall?\uc1\u8217* Then shall you say, \uc1\u8216*Your servant Uriah the Hittite is dead also.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}So the messenger of Joab went to the king at Jerusalem and came and told David all that Joab commanded him concerning the war. Then David was very angry with Joab, and he said to the messenger, \uc1\u8220*Why did you go near the city to fight? Did you not know the would shoot you from the wall? Who smote Abimelech, the son of Jerubbaal? Did not a woman cast an upper millstone upon him from the wall, so that he died in Thebez? Why did you go near the wall?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}Then the messenger said to David, \uc1\u8220*The men boldly attacked us and came out to us in the open field, and so we drove them back even to the entrance of the gate.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}And the archers shot at your servants from the wall; and some of the king\uc1\u8217*s servants are dead.\uc1\u8221* But the messenger said, \uc1\u8220*Your servant Uriah the Hittite is dead also.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}Thereupon David said to the messenger, \uc1\u8220*Thus shall you say to Joab, \uc1\u8216*Let not this thing displease you, for the sword devours one as well as another; persist in your attack upon the city, and overthrow it,\uc1\u8217* and encourage him.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}Now when the wife of Uriah heard that Uriah her husband was dead, she made lamentation for her husband.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}But when the mourning was over, David sent and took her home to his house, and she became his wife and bore him a son. But the thing that David had done displeased Jehovah.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 12}Then Jehovah sent  Nathan to David. And he came to him, and said to him, \uc1\u8220*There were two men in one city, the one rich, the other poor.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}The rich man had very many flocks and herds.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}But the poor man had nothing, except one little ewe lamb, which he had bought. And he nourished it and it grew up with him and with his children. It used to eat of his own morsel, and drink out of his own cup, and lay in his bosom, and was to him as a daughter.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}But there came a traveller to the rich man, and he spared his own flock and did not take from it nor from his own herd to make ready for the traveller who had come to him, but took the poor man\uc1\u8217*s lamb and prepared it for the man who had come to him.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}Then David\uc1\u8217*s anger was greatly aroused against the man, and he said to Nathan, \uc1\u8220*As Jehovah liveth, the man who has done this is worthy of death,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}and he shall restore the lamb , because he showed no pity.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}Therefore Nathan said to David, \uc1\u8220*You are the man! Thus saith Jehovah, the God of Israel, \uc1\u8216*I anointed thee king over Israel and I delivered thee out of the hand of Saul,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}and I gave thee thy master\uc1\u8217*s house and thy master\uc1\u8217*s wives into thy bosom, and gave thee the house of Israel and of Judah, and if that were too little, I would add to you as much again.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}Why have you despised the word of Jehovah by doing that which is evil? You have smitten Uriah the Hittite with the sword, and have taken his wife to be your wife, and have slain him with the sword of the Ammonites.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}Now therefore the sword shall never depart from your house, because you have despised me and have taken the wife of Uriah the Hittite to be your wife.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Thus saith Jehovah, \uc1\u8216*Behold, I will raise up evil against thee out of thine own house, and I will take thy wives from before thine eyes and give them to thy neighbor, and he shall lie with thy wives in the sight of this sun,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}for thou didst it secretly; but I will do this thing before all Israel, and before the sun.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}Then David said to Nathan, \uc1\u8220*I have sinned against Jehovah.\uc1\u8221* And Nathan said to David, \uc1\u8220*Jehovah also put away your sin; you shall not die.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}Yet, because by this deed you have scorned , the child also that is born to you shall surely die.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}And Nathan departed to his house.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
And Jehovah smote the child which Uriah\uc1\u8217*s wife bore to David, so that it fell sick.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}Then David besought God for the child, and fasted and went in and lay all night  upon the earth.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}And the elders of his house stood over him in order to raise him up from the earth; but he would not arise, neither would be eat bread with them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}But on the seventh day the child died. And the servants of David feared to tell him that the child was dead, for they said, \uc1\u8220*Behold while the child was yet alive, we spoke to him, and he hearkened not to our voice; how can we say the child is dead, for he will do some harm!\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}But when David saw that his servants were whispering together, David perceived that the child was dead, and David said to his servants, \uc1\u8220*Is the child dead?\uc1\u8221* And they said, \uc1\u8220*He is dead.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}Then David arose from the earth, and washed and anointed himself, and changed his garments; and he came into the house of Jehovah and worshipped. Then he went to his own house; and he asked for bread and they set it before him and he ate.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}Then said to his servants to him, \uc1\u8220*What is this you have done? You fasted and wept for the child, while it was alive, but when the child died, you arose and ate bread.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}And he said, \uc1\u8220*While the child was yet alive, I fasted and wept; for I said, \uc1\u8216*Who knows whether Jehovah will have mercy, so that the child will live?\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}But now he is dead; why should I fast? Can I bring him back again? I am going to him, but he will not come back to me.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Then David comforted Bathsheba his wife, and went in unto her and lay with her and she  bore a son whose name he called Solomon. And Jehovah loved him,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}and sent a message through Nathan the prophet; and he called his name Jedidiah (The Beloved of Jehovah),  of Jehovah.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}And Joab fought against Rabbah of the Ammonites and took the .{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}Then Joab sent messengers to David, saying, \uc1\u8220*I have fought against Rabbah; also I have taken the water city.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}Now therefore gather the rest of the people together, and encamp against the city, and take it, lest I take the city and it should be called by my name.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}So David gathered all the people together and went to Rabbah and fought against it and took it.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}And he took the crown of Milcom from his head; and its weight was about one hundred and forty pounds of gold, and in it was a precious stone; and it was set on David\uc1\u8217*s head. And he brought away the great amount of spoil that was in the city.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}And he brought away the people who were in it, and put them at the saws and picks and axes of iron and made them  the brickmounds. Even thus he did all the cities of the Ammonites. Then David and all the people returned to Jerusalem.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 13}Now afterwards it came to pass that Absalom the son of David had a beautiful sister, whose name was Tamar; and Amnon the son of David loved her.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}And Amnon was so distressed that he became sick because of his sister Tamar--for she was a virgin--and it seemed to Amnon impossible to do anything to her.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}But Amnon had a friend whose name was Jonadab the son of Shimeah, David\uc1\u8217*s brother, and Jonadab was a very shrewd man.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}And he said to him, \uc1\u8220*Why are you, a king\uc1\u8217*s son, so ill every morning? Will you not tell me?\uc1\u8221* And Amnon said to him, \uc1\u8220*I love Tamar, my brother Absalom\uc1\u8217*s sister.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}And Jonadab said to him, \uc1\u8220*Lie down on your bed, and pretend to be sick. Then when your father comes to see you, say to him, \uc1\u8216*Let my sister Tamar come and give me bread to eat, and prepare the food in my sight, that I may see it and eat from her hand.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}So Amnon lay down and pretended to be sick. And when the king came to see him, Amnon said to the king, \uc1\u8220*Let my sister Tamar come and make a few heart-shaped cakes in my sight, that I may eat from her hand.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}So David sent home to Tamar, saying, \uc1\u8220*Go now to your brother Amnon\uc1\u8217*s house, and prepare food for him.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}So Tamar went to her brother Amnon\uc1\u8217*s house while he lay in bed. And she took dough and kneaded it and made cakes as he looked on, and baked the cakes.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}And she took the pan and poured them out before him, but he refused to eat. And Amnon said, \uc1\u8220*Let all go out from me.\uc1\u8221* And they all went out from him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}And Amnon said to Tamar, \uc1\u8220*Bring the food into the inner room, that I may take from your hand.\uc1\u8221* And Tamar took the cakes which she had made, and brought them into the inner room to Amnon her brother.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}And when she had brought them to him to eat, he took hold of her and said to her, \uc1\u8220*Come, lie with me, my sister.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}And she answered him, \uc1\u8220*No, my brother, do not force me, for it is not so done in Israel; do not commit this impious act of folly.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}And as for me, whither could I carry my shame? and as for you, you would become one of the impious fools in Israel. Now therefore, I beg you, speak to the king, for he will not withhold me from you.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}But he would not hearken to her, but being stronger than she, he violated her and lay with her.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}Then Amnon hated her with great hatred, for the hatred with which he hated her was greater than he love with which he had loved her. And Amnon said to her, \uc1\u8220*Arise, be gone!\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}But she said to him, \uc1\u8220*No, my brother; far greater is the second wrong in sending me away than the first that you did to me.\uc1\u8221* And he would not listen to her, {\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}but called his servant who  and said, \uc1\u8220*Put this woman out from my presence, and bolt the door after her.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}And she wore a long-sleeved tunic, for thus the royal maidens were formerly wont to be clad. Then his servant put her out and bolted the door after her.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}And Tamar put ashes on her head, and rent her long-sleeved tunic which she wore; and she put her hand on her head, and went her way, crying aloud as she went.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}And Absalom her own brother said to her, \uc1\u8220*Has Amnon your brother been with you? But now, my sister, be silent, for he is your brother; do not take this thing to heart.\uc1\u8221* So Tamar dwelt desolate in her brother Absalom\uc1\u8217*s house.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}But when King David heard of all these things, he was very angry, .{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}And Absalom spoke to Amnon neither good nor bad; for Absalom hated Amnon, because he had violated his sister Tamar.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}Now it happened after two years, that Absalom had sheepshearers in Baal Hazor near Ephraim, and Absalom invited all the king\uc1\u8217*s sons.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}And Absalom came to the king and said, \uc1\u8220*See your servant has sheepshearers; let the king, I pray, and his servants go with your servant.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}But the king said to Absalom, \uc1\u8220*No my son, let us not all go, lest we be burdensome to you. And he pressed him; however, he would not go but bade him farewell.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}Then Absalom said, \uc1\u8220*If not, then let my brother Amnon go with us.\uc1\u8221* And the king said, \uc1\u8220*Why should he go with you?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}But when Absalom pressed him, he let Amnon and all the king\uc1\u8217*s sons go with him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}Then Absalom commanded his servants, saying, \uc1\u8220*See to it, when Amnon\uc1\u8217*s heart is merry with wine, and when I say to you, \uc1\u8216*Smite Amnon,\uc1\u8217* then kill him. Fear not; have not I commanded you? Be brave and show yourselves valiant men!\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}And the servants of Absalom did to Amnon as Absalom had commanded. Then all the king\uc1\u8217*s sons arose and each mounted his mule and fled.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}And while they were on the way, the news came to David: \uc1\u8220*Absalom has slain all the king\uc1\u8217*s sons so that there is not one of them left.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}Then the king arose and tore his clothes and lay on the earth; and all his servants .{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}And Jonadab the son of Shimeah, David\uc1\u8217*s brother, answered and said, \uc1\u8220*Let not my lord suppose that they have killed all the young men, the king\uc1\u8217*s sons, for Amnon only is dead, since by the statement of Absalom this was decided from the day of the violation of his sister Tamar.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}Now therefore let not my lord the king take this thing to heart, to think that all the king\uc1\u8217*s sons are dead; for Amnon only is dead.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34} And when the  lifted up his eyes and looked, there were many people coming . {\super\f1\cf2\fs24 35}And Jonadab said to the king, \uc1\u8220*There the king\uc1\u8217*s sons are coming, as your servant said so it has come to pass.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 36}As soon as he had finished speaking, the king\uc1\u8217*s sons came and lifted up their voices and wept; and the king also and all his servants wept loudly.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 37}But Absalom fled and went to Talmai the son of Amihud, king of Geshur, and David mourned continually for his son.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 38} and remained there three years.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 39} longed to go out to Absalom, for he was comforted for the death of Amnon.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 14}Now when Joab the son of Zeruiah perceived that the king\uc1\u8217*s heart was favorable towards Absalom,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}Joab sent to Tekoa and brought from there a wise woman and said to her, \uc1\u8220*Pretend to be a mourner and put on mourning garments and do not anoint yourself with oil, but become like a woman who has been many days mourning for one dead,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}and go to the king and speak thus with him.\uc1\u8221* So Joab put the words in her mouth.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}And the Tekoite woman came to the king, and prostrated herself upon the ground and did obeisance, crying, \uc1\u8220*Help, O king\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}And the king said to her, \uc1\u8220*What is wrong with you?\uc1\u8221* And he said, \uc1\u8220*Verily, I am a widow and my husband is dead.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}And your maid-servant had two sons, and these two quarelled in the field when there was no one to part them, and one smote the other and killed him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}And now the whole clan has risen up against your maid-servant and say, \uc1\u8216*Deliver up the slayer of his brother, that we may put him to death for the life of his brother whom he has killed, and we will destroy the heir.\uc1\u8217* Thus they will quench my remaining coal so as to leave to my husband neither name nor remnant on the face of the earth.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Then the king said to the woman, \uc1\u8220*Go to your house and I will give orders regarding you.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}And the woman of Tekoa said to the king, \uc1\u8220*My lord, O king, the guilt be on me and on my father\uc1\u8217*s house; and the king and his throne be innocent.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}And the king said, \uc1\u8220*Whoever saith anything to you bring him to me and he shall not touch you again.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Then she said, \uc1\u8220*I pray, let the king swear by Jehovah thy God, not to let the avenger of blood destroy and not let them exterminate my son.\uc1\u8221* And he said, \uc1\u8220*As Jehovah liveth, not one hair of your son shall fall to the ground.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Then the woman said, \uc1\u8220*Let your maid-servant, I pray you, speak a word to my lord the king.\uc1\u8221* And he said, \uc1\u8220*Speak.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}And the woman said, \uc1\u8220*Why then do you devise such a thing against the people of God? For in rendering this decision the king is as one that is guilty, in that the king does not bring back his banished one.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}{This verse will need special attention.} For we die and are as water spilt on the ground, which cannot be gathered up again; and God will not take away the life of him who devises means not to keep in banishment one who is banished.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}Now the reason why I have come to speak this word to my lord the king is because the people made me afraid, and your maid-servant said, \uc1\u8216*I will now speak to the king; it may be that the king will perform the request of his servant.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}For the king will hear, to deliver his servant out of the hand of the man who seeks to destroy me and my son from the heritage of  .\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}Then your maid-servant said, \uc1\u8216*Let the word of my lord the king be a comfort, for like the Messenger of God is my lord the king to hear good and evil.\uc1\u8217* And Jehovah thy God be with you.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}Then the king answered and said to the woman, \uc1\u8220*Do not conceal from me, I pray, anything that I may ask you.\uc1\u8221* And the woman said, \uc1\u8220*Let my lord the king now speak.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}And the king said, \uc1\u8220*Was the hand of Joab with you in all this?\uc1\u8221* And the woman answered and said, \uc1\u8220*As sure as you live, my lord the king, I cannot turn to the right hand or to the left from all that my lord the king has spoken, for your servant Joab bade me put all these words in the mouth of your maid-servant;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}in order to change the face of affairs has your servant done this thing. But my lord is wise, according to the wisdom of the Messenger of God, so that he knows all things that are in the earth.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}And the king said to Joab, \uc1\u8220*See now, I have granted this request; go therefore, bring the young man Absalom back.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}Then Joab fell to the ground on his face and did obeisance and blessed the king. And Joab said, \uc1\u8220*To-day your servant knows that I have found favor in your sight, my lord, O king, in that the king has granted the request of his servant.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}So Joab arose and went to Geshur, and brought Absalom back to Jerusalem.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}And the king said, \uc1\u8220*Let him live apart in his own house, but my face he shall not see.\uc1\u8221* So Absalom lived apart to his own house, but he did not see the king\uc1\u8217*s face.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}Now no man in Israel was so praiseworthy for his beauty as Absalom: from the sole of his foot even to the crown of his head there was no blemish in him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}And when he shaved his head--at the end every year he cut it, because it was heavy on him, therefore he cut it--he would weigh his hair, about six pounds according to the royal standard of weight.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}And to Absalom there were born three sons and one daughter, whose name was Tamar--she was a beautiful woman.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}And Absalom dwelt two years in Jerusalem, without seeing the king\uc1\u8217*s face.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}Then Absalom sent for Joab to send him to the king; but he would not come to him. Then he sent again a second time, but he would not come.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}Therefore he said to his servants, \uc1\u8220*See Joab\uc1\u8217*s field is near mine, where he has barley; go and set it on fire.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}Then Joab arose, and came to Absalom at his house and said to him, \uc1\u8220*Why have your servants set my field on fire?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}And Absalom answered Joab, \uc1\u8220*Behold, I sent to you, saying, \uc1\u8216*Come here that I may send you to the king, to say, \uc1\u8220*Why have I come from Geshur? It were better for me to be there still.\uc1\u8221*\uc1\u8217* Now therefore let me see the king\uc1\u8217*s face, and if there be guilt in me, let him kill me.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}And when Joab went to the king and told him, he called Absalom. And he came to the king and bowed himself with his face to the ground before the king. Then the king kissed Absalom.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 15}Now later Absalom prepared a chariot and horses and fifty men to run before him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}And Absalom used to rise early and stand beside the way which led to the gate, and every man who had a suit to come before the king for judgment, Absalom would call to himself and say, \uc1\u8220*Of what city are you?\uc1\u8221* And when he replied, \uc1\u8220*Your servant is of one of the tribes of Israel\uc1\u8221*,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}Absalom said to him, \uc1\u8220*Evidently your claims are good and right; but there is no man deputed by the king to hear you.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Absalom said moreover, \uc1\u8220*O that someone would make me judge in the land, that to me might come every man who has any suit or cause, and I would give him justice!\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}And whenever man came near to do obeisance, he would put out his hand and take hold of him and kiss him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}And in this way Absalom did to all the Israelites who came to the king for judgment. So Absalom stole the hearts of the men of Israel.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}And at the end of  years, Absalom said to the king, \uc1\u8220*I would like to go and pay my vow, which I have vowed to Jehovah, in Hebron.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}For your servant vowed the following vow while I abode at Geshur in Aram, \uc1\u8216*If Jehovah shall indeed bring me back to Jerusalem, I will serve Jehovah .\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}Then the king said to him, Go in peace. So he arose, and went to Hebron.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}But Absalom sent emissaries into all the tribes of Israel, saying, \uc1\u8220*As soon as you hear the sound of the trumpet, then say, \uc1\u8216*Absalom has become king in Hebron.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}And with Absalom went two hundred men from Jerusalem, who were invited and went in their innocence and knew nothing at all.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}And Absalom sent  Ahithophel the Gilonite, David\uc1\u8217*s counsellor, from his city Giloh, while he was offering the sacrifices. And the conspiracy was strong, for the people with Absalom kept increasing.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}And when a messenger came to David, saying, \uc1\u8220*The heart of the men of Israel has gone after Absalom\uc1\u8221*,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}David said to all his servants who were with him at Jerusalem, \uc1\u8220*Up, let us flee; for otherwise there will be for us no escape from Absalom. Make haste to depart, lest he quickly overtake us and bring down evil upon us and put the city to the edge of the sword.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}Then the king\uc1\u8217*s servants said to the king, \uc1\u8220*Just as our lord the king decides, we are your servants.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}So the king went out, and all his household with him. And the king left behind ten concubines to keep the palace.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}And the king and all the people who followed him went out and stood at the last house,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}while all his officers passed beside him, and all the Cherethites and all the Pelethites and all , six hundred who had followed him from Gath passed on before the king.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}Then said the king to Ittai the Gittite, \uc1\u8220*Why will you also go with us? Return and stay with the king; for you are a foreigner and an exile from your own land.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}Yesterday you came and to-day shall I make you wander with us, while I go whither I may? Return, and take your fellow countrymen back with you; and .\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}But Ittai answered the king, and said, \uc1\u8220*As Jehovah liveth and as my lord the king liveth, wherever my lord the king shall be--whether for death or for life--there will your servant be.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}And David said to Ittai, \uc1\u8220*Well then, go, and pass on.\uc1\u8221* So Ittai the Gittite passed on with all his men and all the little ones that were with him.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}{This verse will need special attention.} And all the inhabitants of the land were weeping loudly as all the people passed on. While the king stood in the Kidron valley, the people were passing by before him toward the olive tree in the wilderness.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}And there was Zadok and  with him, bearing the ark of the covenant of God,  until all the people had all passed out out of the city.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}And the king said to Zadok and Abiathar, \uc1\u8220*Carry back the ark of God into the city. If I shall find favor in the eyes of Jehovah, he will bring me back, and show me both it and his dwelling.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}But if he say, \uc1\u8216*I have no delight in thee\uc1\u8217*; then here am I, let him do to me as seemeth good to him.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}{This verse will need special attention.} The king also said to Zadok and Abiathar the priests, \uc1\u8220*Behold, return to the city in peace and your two sons with you, Ahimaaz your son and Jonathan the son Abiathar.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}See, I am going to delay at the fords of the wilderness, until word comes from you to inform me.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}Therefore Zadok and Abiathar carried the ark of God again to Jerusalem, and they remained there.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}But David went up the ascent to the Mount of Olives, weeping as he went, and with his head covered and his feet bare. All the people who were with him also covered each his head, and also went up, weeping as they went.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}And when David was told, \uc1\u8220*Ahithophel is among the conspirators with Absalom\uc1\u8221*, David said, \uc1\u8220*O Jehovah, I pray, turn the counsel of Ahithophel to foolishness.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}And when David came to the summit, where one worships God, there came to meet him Hushai the Archite with his garment rent and earth upon his head.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}And David said to him, \uc1\u8220*If you go on with me you will be a burden to me.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}But if you return to the city, and say to Absalom, \uc1\u8216*Your brothers have gone away and the king your father has gone away after them, I will be thy servant, O king; I have been your father\uc1\u8217*s servant in the past, so now I will be your servant\uc1\u8217*, thus you can defeat for me the counsel of Ahithophel.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 35}And have you not here with you Zadok and Abiathar the priests? Everything that you hear from the king\uc1\u8217*s palace tell it to Zadok and Abiathar the priests.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 36}See, they have there with them their two sons, Ahimaaz, Zadok\uc1\u8217*s son, and Jonathan, Abiathar\uc1\u8217*s son; and by them you shall send to me everything that you shall hear.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 37}So Hushai, David\uc1\u8217*s friend, came into the city, when Absalom came to Jerusalem.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 16}And David was a little past the summit, when Ziba the servant of Meribaal met him with a pair of asses saddled, and on them two hundred loaves of bread, and a hundred bunches of raisins, and a hundred cakes of preserved fruits, and a skin of wine.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}And the king said to Ziba, \uc1\u8220*\uc1\u8221* And Ziba answered, \uc1\u8220*The asses are for the king\uc1\u8217*s household to ride on, and the bread and the preserved fruit for the young men to eat, and the wine, that those who are faint in the wilderness may drink.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}And the king said, \uc1\u8220*And where is thy master\uc1\u8217*s son?\uc1\u8221* And Ziba answered the king, \uc1\u8220*He remains there at Jerusalem, for he thinks, \uc1\u8216*To-day will the house of Israel give me back my father\uc1\u8217*s kingdom.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Then said the king to Ziba, \uc1\u8220*All is now yours that belongs to Meribaal.\uc1\u8221* And Ziba said, \uc1\u8220*I do obeisance. Let me find further favor in your sight, my lord, the king.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}And when King David came to Bahurim, there came out from there a man of the family of the house of Saul, whose name was Shimei the son of Gera, constantly cursing as he came.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}And he cast stones at David and all the officers of King David and at all the people and all the mighty warriors at his right hand and at his left.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}And thus Shimei said as he cursed, \uc1\u8220*Begone, begone, bloody and vile scoundrel!{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Jehovah has brought back upon you all the blood of the house of Saul, in whose place you have reigned; and Jehovah hath delivered the kingdom into the hand of Absalom your son; and behold now you are in your misfortune, for you are a bloody man!\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}Then Abishai the son of Zeruiah said to the king, \uc1\u8220*Why should this dead dog curse my lord the king? Let me go over now and take off his head.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}But the king said, \uc1\u8220*What have I in common with you, you sons of Zeruiah? If he curses when Jehovah hath said to him, \uc1\u8216*Curse David!\uc1\u8217* then who shall say, \uc1\u8216*Why have you done so?\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}And David said to Abishai and to all his officers, \uc1\u8220*See, my son who came from my bowels seeks my life; how much more this Benjamite! Let him curse, for Jehovah hath bidden him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Perhaps Jehovah will look on my affliction and repay me good instead of this cursing that he hath sent to-day.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}So David and his men went along the way; but Shimei went along on the hillside parallel with him, cursing as he went, and threw stones and continually cast dust at him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}Then the king and all the people who were with him, arrived weary   and he refreshed himself there.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}And Absalom with all the men of Israel, came to Jerusalem, and Ahithophel was with him.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}Now when Hushai the Archite, David\uc1\u8217*s friend, came to Absalom, Hushai said to Absalom, \uc1\u8220*May the king live, may the king live!\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}But Absalom said to Hushai, \uc1\u8220*Is this your love for your friend? Why did you not go with your friend?\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}Then Hushai answered Absalom, \uc1\u8220*No! for whom Jehovah and his people and all the men of Israel have chosen, to him will I belong, and with him will I remain.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}And in the second place, whom should I serve? Should it not be his son? As I have served your father, so will I serve you.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}Then Absalom said to Ahithophel, \uc1\u8220*Give your counsel as to what we shall do.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}And Ahithophel said to Absalom, \uc1\u8220*Go in unto your father\uc1\u8217*s concubines whom he has left to keep the palace; and all Israel will hear that you have made yourself abhorrent to your father, and the hands of all who are on your side will be strengthed.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}So they pitched for Absalom the tent on the top of the house; and Absalom went in unto his father\uc1\u8217*s concubines in the sight of all Israel.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}And the counsel of Ahitophel, which he gave in those days, was regarded as if one inquired of the word of God--so was all the counsel of Ahithophel regarded by David and Absalom.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 17}Moreover Ahithophel said to Absalom, \uc1\u8220*Let me now choose out twelve thousand men, and I will arise and pursue after David to-night;{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}thus I will come upon him when he is tired and weak and will storm him into a panic and all the people who are with him will flee; and I will smite the king alone,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}and I will bring back all the people to you .   all the people shall be at peace.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}And the advice pleased Absalom, and all the elders of Israel.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}Then Absalom Said, \uc1\u8220*Call now Hushai the Archite also, and let us hear likewise what he has to say.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}And when Hushai came to Absalom, Absalom spoke to him, saying, \uc1\u8220*Thus Ahitophel has spoken; shall we act upon his advice? If not, you give advice.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}Then Hushai said to Absalom, \uc1\u8220*The counsel that Ahithophel has given this time is not good.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Hushai said moreover, \uc1\u8220*You know your father and his men, that they are mighty warriors and of angry temper, like a bear robbed of her cubs in the field. Furthermore your father is a man of war and will not remain at night with the people.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}Even now he has hidden himself in one of the caves or in some other place. And in case some of  fall at the first, whoever hears it will say, \uc1\u8216*There is a slaughter among the people who follow Absalom.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}Then even he that is valiant, whose heart is like the heart of a lion, will completely lose courage; for all Israel knows that your father is a mighty warrior, and they who are with him are valiant men.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}But I counsel, Let all Israel be gathered to you, from Dan to Beersheba, as many as the sand that is by the sea, with you yourself marching in the midst of them.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}So shall we come upon him in some place where he has been discovered, and we will light upon him as the dew falls on the ground; and of him and of all the men who are with him there shall not be left even one.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}But if he has withdrawn into a city, then all Israel will bring ropes to that city, and we will draw it to the valley, until not even a small stone is found there.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}And Absalom and all the men of Israel said, \uc1\u8220*The counsel of Hushai the Archite is better than the counsel of Ahithophel.\uc1\u8221* For Jehovah had ordained to defeat the good counsel of Ahithophel, in order that Jehovah might bring evil upon Absalom.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}Then Hushai said to Zadok and to Abiathar the priests, \uc1\u8220*Thus and thus did Ahithophel counsel Absalom and the elders of Israel; and thus and thus have I counselled.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}Now therefore send quickly and tell David, saying, \uc1\u8216*Do not spend this night at the fords of the wilderness, but by all means cross over, lest the king and all the people with him be swallowed up.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}Now Jonathan and Ahimaaz were staying at Enrogel; and a maid-servant was to go and bring them news, and they were to go and tell King David, for they must not be seen to come into the city.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}But a lad saw them, and told Absalom. Then they both went away quickly and entered into the house of a man in Bahurim, who had a well in his court into which they descended.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}And the woman took and spread the covering over the mouth of the well, and strewed dried fruit upon it, so that nothing was known.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}And when Absalom\uc1\u8217*s servants came to the woman to the house and said, \uc1\u8220*Where are Ahimaaz and Jonathan?\uc1\u8221* the woman answered them, \uc1\u8220*They are gone over the water brook.\uc1\u8221* And when they had sought and could find nothing, they returned to Jerusalem.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}But as soon as they had gone away they came up out of the well, and went and told King David and said to David, \uc1\u8220*Arise, cross quickly over the water for thus has Ahitophel counselled in regard to you.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}Then David and all the people who were with him arose and they crossed over the Jordan. By daybreak there was not one left behind who had not gone over the Jordan.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}But when Ahitophel saw that his counsel had not been carried out, he saddled his ass and arose, and went to his house, to his city. And when he had given command concerning his house, he strangled himself, and he died and was buried in his father\uc1\u8217*s sepulchre.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Then David came to Mahanaim. And Absalom passed over the Jordan, together with all the men of Israel.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}And Absalom set Amasa over the army in the place of Joab. Now Amasa was the son of , who had come in marriage to , the sister of Zeruiah, Joab\uc1\u8217*s mother.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}And Israel and Absalom encamped in the land of Gilead.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}{This verse will need special attention.} But when David came to Mahanaim, Shobi the son of Nahash of the Ammonite Rabbah, and Machir the son of Ammiel of Lodebar, and Barzillai the Gileadite of Rogelim,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}brought couches, rugs, bowls, and earthen vessels, and wheat, barley, meal, parched grain, beans, lentils,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}honey, curds, sheep, and calves for David, and for the people who were with him, to eat; for they thought, \uc1\u8220*The people are hungry and weary and thirsty in the wilderness.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 18}Then David mustered the people who were with him, and appointed over them commanders of thousands and of hundreds.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}And David  the people into three divisions, one third was under the command of Joab, another third under Abishai the son of Zeruiah, Joab\uc1\u8217*s brother, and another third under the command of Ittai the Gittite. And the king said to the people, \uc1\u8220*I also will surely go out with you.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}{This verse will need special attention.} But the people said, \uc1\u8220*You shall not go out; for if we flee away, no one will care for us, or if half of us die, no one will care for us, for you are equal to ten thousand of us. Also it is now better for you to be ready to help us from the city.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}And the king said to them, \uc1\u8220*I will do what you think best!\uc1\u8221* So the king stood by the side of the gate, while all the people went out by hundreds and by thousands.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}And the king commanded Joab, and Abishai, and Ittai, saying, \uc1\u8220*Deal gently for my sake with the young man, with Absalom!\uc1\u8221* And all the people heard when the king gave all the commanders the order regarding Absalom.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}So the people went out into the field against Israel. And the battle was in the forest of Ephraim.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}And the people of Israel were smitten there before the servants of David, so that the slaughter on that day was great--twenty thousand men.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}And the battle was spread out over the whole country; and the forest devoured more that day than the sword.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}And Absalom happened to meet the servants of David. And Absalom was riding upon his mule, and the mule went under the thick boughs of a great oak and his head caught fast in the oak, and he was  between heaven and earth, while the mule that was under him went on.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}And when a certain man saw it, he told Joab and said, \uc1\u8220*Behold, I saw Absalom hanging in an oak.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Then Joab said to the man who told him, \uc1\u8220*So you saw him! Why did you not smite him there to the ground? And my part would have been to give you ten shekels of silver and a girdle.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}But the man said to Joab, \uc1\u8220*If I were to feel the weight of a thousand shekels of silver in my hand I would not put forth my hand against the king\uc1\u8217*s son, for in our hearing the king charged you and Abishai and Ittai, saying, \uc1\u8216*Take care of the young man Absalom.\uc1\u8217*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}Or if I had treacherously taken his life, nothing would have been hidden from the king, and you yourself would have stood aloof.\uc1\u8221*{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}Then Joab answered, \uc1\u8220*I will not tarry thus with you.\uc1\u8221* And he took three  in his hand, and thrust them into Absalom\uc1\u8217*s heart, while he was still alive in the midst of the oak.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}And ten young men who bore Joab\uc1\u8217*s armor gathered about and smote Absalom and put him to death.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}Then Joab blew the trumpet, and the people returned from pursuing Israel; for Joab held back the people.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}And they took Absalom and cast him into the great pit in the forest, and raised over him a heap of stones. And all Israel fled each to his home.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}But Absalom had already in his lifetime taken and reared up for himself the pillar which is in the King\uc1\u8217*s Dale; for he said, \uc1\u8220*I have no son to keep my name in remembrance; and he named the pillar after his own name. Therefore it is called \uc1\u8216*Absalom\uc1\u8217*s Monument,\uc1\u8217* to this day.\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
